<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="58" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,1662,1867]" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,1662,1687]" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">Distribution.</emphasis>
PALEARCTIC. Widespread in northern and central Europe, ranging from 
<collectingCountry box="[1202,1285,1662,1687]" name="Iceland" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">Iceland</collectingCountry>
and northern Fennoscandia to the Spanish Pyrenees and 
<collectingCountry box="[658,747,1698,1723]" name="France" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">Corsica</collectingCountry>
. Isolated East Asian records (
<bibRefCitation author="Hennig" box="[1099,1271,1698,1723]" pageId="7" pageNumber="58" refString="Hennig, W. (1973 b) Anthomyiidae [part]. In: Lindner, E. (Ed.), Die Fliegen der palaearktischen Region, 7 (1), Lieferung 296. E. Schweizerbart, Stuttgart, pp. 513 - 592." type="journal article" year="1973" yearSuffix="b">
Hennig, 
<number box="[1201,1258,1698,1723]" pageId="7" pageNumber="58" value="1973.0">1973</number>
b
</bibRefCitation>
) from Irkutsk (
<collectingCountry box="[158,236,1734,1759]" name="Russia" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">Russia</collectingCountry>
) and Harbin (
<collectingCountry box="[410,480,1734,1759]" name="China" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">China</collectingCountry>
) are questionable and possibly refer to the closely related boreal and Holarctic 
<taxonomicName box="[151,392,1772,1795]" class="Insecta" family="Anthomyiidae" genus="Pegomya" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="transgressa">
<emphasis box="[151,392,1772,1795]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">Pegomya transgressa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see next species).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="58" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,1662,1867]" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,295,1806,1831]" pageId="7" pageNumber="58">Biology.</emphasis>
